Here’s what is happening in and affecting South Africa today: Prescribed assets: The South African Communist Party has called on the ruling ANC to reconsider its stance on prescribed assets, which will force pension funds to invest in government stock. The ANC is set to discuss this and other issues when it holds its policy conference at the end of July. [BusinessDay] SA Express: South Africa’s International Air Services Council has cancelled all licences and related route rights currently allocated to regional state-owned airline SA Express (SAX) with immediate effect – pointing to the end of another regional airline in South Africa. SAX went into business rescue in February 2020. It was placed in provisional liquidation since April 2020 and has not operated since. [News24] Electricity debt: The City of Johannesburg says it is currently considering a debt write-off for billions of rands in electricity debt accumulated by Soweto residents. The long-standing dispute between residents and Eskom saw the power utility disconnect some households from the grid, sparking several protests across Soweto. [EWN] Load shedding: The ongoing load shedding crisis has led to a spike in insurance claims as sensitive electronics and household appliances are damaged by the continuous power cuts. Load shedding has also led to an increase in both motor vehicle accidents and home burglaries as criminals take advantage of the darkness. [Moneyweb] Markets: South Africa’s rand rose against the dollar and stocks fell on Wednesday, after U.S. inflation for June came in higher than expected, raising bets about another big Federal Reserve interest rate increase. The rand is currently trading at R16.97/$, R17.02/€ and R20.14/£. The price of Brent crude oil today is $100.30rand /barrel. [Reuters]